Type vs Interface

Both `type` and `interface` can describe object shapes, but they have important differences.

### Similarities

```typescript
// Both work for object types
interface UserInterface {
  name: string;
  age: number;
}

type UserType = {
  name: string;
  age: number;
};

// Both support generics
interface Box<T> { content: T; }
type Box<T> = { content: T; };
```

### Key Differences

| Feature | Interface | Type Alias |
|---------|-----------|-----------|
| Declaration merging | Yes | No |
| Extends | `extends` | Intersection (`&`) |
| Unions | No | Yes |
| Tuples | No | Yes |
| Primitives | No | Yes |
| Mapped types | No | Yes |
| Performance | Better for object types | Better for complex types |

### Declaration Merging

Interfaces can be merged across multiple declarations:

```typescript
interface User {
  name: string;
}

interface User {
  age: number;
}

// User now has both name and age

// Type aliases cannot be merged
// type User = { name: string }; // Error: Duplicate identifier
```

### When to Use What

| Use Case | Recommendation |
|----------|---------------|
| Public API / Library | Interface |
| Object shapes | Interface |
| Union types | Type |
| Primitive aliases | Type |
| Tuple types | Type |
| Mapped types | Type |
| Utility types | Type |

> **Key Point:** Prefer `interface` for public APIs and object shapes; use `type` for unions, primitives, and complex type transformations.

codeExample:
// Interface for public API
export interface ApiResponse<T> {
  status: number;
  data: T;
  message: string;
}

// Type for unions
type Status = "idle" | "loading" | "success" | "error";
type Id = string | number;

// Type for tuples
type Point = [x: number, y: number];

// Interface can be extended
interface BaseEntity {
  id: number;
  createdAt: Date;
}

interface User extends BaseEntity {
  name: string;
  email: string;
}

// Type for intersection
type AdminUser = User & { role: "admin"; permissions: string[] };
